name: ALDI
review_text:
Historically have provided feedback to ALDI with no response on the issues of diversity, gender representation in top management, product quality and customer service. Advised in a job interview that 'despite how talented I was, I would not be getting a job as an Area General Manager.' Less experienced and less knowledgeable interviewees of the German chain, differentiated by Aldi Nord and Aldi Sud successful.

On the issue of product quality and customer service. Followed up a query for my Mother in 2021/2022 regarding several items, in the shopping trolley category. The Brunswick Store provided items that did not match the photographs in the retailers magazine and when the correct product was provided, the measurements were inconsistent and not accurate to advertised material. No response was provided to the Customer Complaint. Lift up your game Aldi Sud.

review_text: Im always confused by this store. Sometimes its well stocked, and sometimes not. But particularly at this store, why have several different types of shopping trolley, that don't connect to each other, and so its really difficult to get your token or $2 coin back? When I mentioned this to staff, they admitted they used 3 different trolley systems here! Not so at Aldi in Echuca which is so well stocked and efficient and uses one trolley system - it might be on a different planet!

Because it is so busy, the bread often runs out / low. So again, be early.

review_text: This is a good Also, in that you can always get a car spot in the car park, no matter how busy. However one of the two lifts has been out of order for several months now with no indication if being fixed. This is even after this particular store has been renovated and 'improved' at great expense. Today there was a backlog of people waiting for the lift for more than five minutes. It seems like something pretty simple that could be arranged to be fixed by such a wealthy and large organisation!

name: ALDI
review_text:
Good sized store! The location is unbeatable--- right on Sydney road and super easy to get a park for my car either at the front or on the side streets right near the store.

Shelves are always regularly replenished and the quality of the fresh produce is always decent!

The staff at this store are particularly friendly!  I'm a regular shopper at various Aldi stores in and around the city, but the workers here by far are the nicest I've come across!  They're usually the same ones when I go in to shop and each time it's always a pleasant experience :)

review_text: Awesome customer experience.  Attended the check out and the cashier noticed one of my items was missing a critical component.  He left the service seat and literally ran to source the missing part.  His positive disposition was so refreshing as many customer service staff don‚Äôt value the customer.  During my shop I observed that the store was meticulously maintained, shelves stocked, arranged and clean.  I asked a couple of staff questions about the location of products and they stoped their task and took me to the relevant section of the store.  I‚Äôm loyal to the Aldi brand and I‚Äôm grateful that this store has recently been upgraded.  Parking is more than adequate.  The wine, beer and spirit selection is comprehensive.  I have no hesitation recommending the Brunswick Aldi store to anyone who values superior customer service and an exceptionally well run store.

Weird thing to say it's not my neighbourhood so i finished my shopping took the already opened coffee pods to counter and asked do I get a discount its the last box and its opened reply no we don't do that but I was desperate and said I'll take it but does it have all the pods he counted and no there wasn't.  So disappointed in my customer service or lack of  i received  and selling the last already opened not completely full pod box at full price. I didn't need to purchase but like I said was desperate for that product.
At every Aldi store  I have gone to I have always received excellent helpful customer service every visit but Sorry Brunswick store not from you very poor please learn from your mistakes to improve for the future. If I was a mystery shopper it came across as below average this visit.

name: ALDI
review_text:
Appalling customer service. Letting the international Aldi brand down.

Upon entering I didn‚Äôt have a coin for the trolleys, and really only wanted to do a small shop. I asked an Aldi staff member with an earpiece in (assuming he was management), if they had any baskets I could use. His reply: ‚ÄúAldi don‚Äôt do baskets!‚Äù, and he turned away. I accepted this abrupt sweeping statement, without letting him know he was wrong. I proceeded to use a discarded vegetable box for my shopping.

At checkout I was greeted with ‚Äúcan I check your bag?‚Äù. I couldn‚Äôt believe it. I had a rucksack on my back, with both straps over my shoulders, carrying my shopping in a box by hand. I asked why he wanted to check my back, his response was as abrupt as the first guy; ‚Äúif you don‚Äôt like it don‚Äôt shop here‚Äù.

I felt instantly accused of shoplifting.

How awful the customer service? Are they not trained about customer retention, and word of mouth?

Use discretion when asking to invade someone‚Äôs private space by demanding to check their bag. Power trip?

I tried to educate him on the law, but he repeated ‚Äúdon‚Äôt shop here if you don‚Äôt like it‚Äù.

The ARA recommends that shopkeepers only check small, personal bags (the size of A4 paper or smaller) when they are certain the bag conceals unpaid-for goods from the store.

The ARA's advice is subject to the consumer‚Äôs right to say ‚Äòno‚Äô to a bag search.

Educate your staff ALDI. And give some urgent customer service training.

I‚Äôm a journalist, and a traveller, and have experienced Aldi stores worldwide. This is the worst I‚Äôve been to.

review_text:
No aldimobile phone service in the aldi!! How embarrassing. Also noticed this at one other aldi store.
Special buys are cheap quality (often available for similar price elsewhere in a warranty backed name brand if you look) and aldi don't honor consumer law requiring them to offer repair or replace in case of faulty items (major issue for things like LEDs bought for multilight fittings which are one off stock items they ship totally different spec LEDs in subsequent orders) grocery range is extremely limited, impossible to do a full shop here so we just use aldi for a few items like nappies.  Checkout process really demonstrates Aldis customer focus. Items are scanned and push at you, if you are too slow they end up on the floor and the checkout staff keep going. Surely they could do better and remain competitive.
Too bad as in the early days of aldi the special buys offered real value but they haven't maintained the quality or improved the store offerings.

name: ALDI
review_text:
Aldi at Chadstone Shopping Centre
Visited on 23/11/2021

Chadstone shopping Centre expects very standard from retail outlets, and Aldi keeps the standard up.

The renovated supermarket is bright, contrasted by the black vinyl floor tiles. The isles are very wide, and definitely wheelchair friendly.

Like a typical Aldi store, there are not many staff around if you need help. However, it is always not a problem to go to the cashier to page someone to come to your rescue.

The staff do work efficiently in accordance to the foot traffic in the store, and extra check out bays are open if the customer queue gets too long.

I meet a staff holding a stock-count gadget, and ask whether he is the Duty Manager. Once confirmed, I compliment his store for cleanliness, well stocked, and the variey of items on sale.

I read some bad reviews of staff service provision. I hope the management can look into this matter, and provide more training for them

name: ALDI
review_text:
Some really well priced products. The range can be limited but the cheese, chocolate and biscuits are excellent.

I've found that some specialty items (eg specific baby food flavours) have been out of stock a fair bit. It may be due to external factors though.

name: ALDI
review_text:
I spent more than $100 at ALDI, I have invoice and I bought two pairs of these scissors($3.99), and I found them very difficult to use.
When I was in the checkout line, I tried to return a pair of scissors, but the clerk told me to wait for the manager.
I waited for 15 minutes, but the manager came out and had a look and told me to keep waiting. After a while, the manager came out and, without any reason, told me straight away that I couldn't return it.
I asked if there was any reason why I could return it. I bought enough two and just returned a brand new one, which I will not use in the future. I will return it to you for resale. But he was silent, just looking at me all the time, not talking, quite boring, is no longer the scissors problem, the store manager to deal with the problem is like this?

review_text:
I purchased the SOHL Chest of 3 Draws and the matching Tall Boy, cost $149 dollars each for a total of $298.  They looked great in the catalog. Don't waste your time, once they were unpacked it was clear that they were factory seconds, very poor quality. One draw had a drill hole in the front. The handles didn't fit properly and the screws pulled right through. So as you opened the draw the handles would come off (on one side of the draws), the top was bowed, the gaps were terrible, and the draws would grab and not open smoothly. Too many things to mention. A waste of 2 hours in assembly and getting them back to Aldi for a refund.

Total waste of time and money, spare yourself the pain, spend a bit extra.

The ALDI at Chadstone is like any other ADLI, you get most the items you need at a cheaper price compare to other major supermarkets.

review_text: Aldi's Chadstone continues to be the worst in customer service. They repeatedly allow customers to not socially distance during COVID-19 at the counter. However, I'm forced to rush to bag my items while customers are allowed to stand <0.5m from the EFTPOS machine before I've even paid! When I've raised this with the check out clerk, I'm met with mute apathy. Customer service just plain sucks at this store. It's not an isolated incident.

Shoppers please check your docket VERY CAREFULLY as Aldi management failed to prevent their staff from taking "extra money" from their honest and trusting customers, and they are "good at" playing "re-no-fund" botched game. Nasty and dishonest! It is time to go elsewhere for your groceries, people!

review_text:
Very busy ALDI Aldi¬†(stylised as¬†ALDI) is the common brand of two German family owned¬†discount supermarket¬†chains¬†with over 10,000 stores in 20 countries, and an estimated combined turnover of more than ‚Ç¨50 billion. Based in Germany, the chain was founded by brothers¬†Karl¬†and¬†Theo Albrecht¬†in 1946 when they took over their mother's store in¬†Essen, which had been in operation since 1913. The business was split into two separate groups in 1960, that later became¬†Aldi Nord, headquartered in Essen, and¬†Aldi S√ºd, headquartered in¬†M√ºlheim.¬†In 1962, they introduced the name¬†Aldi¬†(a¬†syllabic abbreviation¬†for¬†Albrecht¬†Diskont),¬†which is pronounced¬†[ÀàaldiÀê]¬†(listen). In Germany, Aldi Nord and Aldi S√ºd have been financially and legally separate since 1966, although both divisions' names may appear as if they were a single enterprise with certain¬†store brands¬†or when negotiating with¬†contractor¬†companies. The formal business name is Aldi Einkauf GmbH & Compagnie, oHG.Aldi's German operations consist of Aldi Nord's 35 individual regional companies with about 2,500 stores in western, northern, and eastern Germany, and Aldi S√ºd's 32 regional companies with 1,600 stores in western and southern Germany.[8]¬†Internationally, Aldi Nord operates in Denmark, France, the Benelux countries, Portugal, Spain and Poland, while Aldi S√ºd operates in Ireland, Great Britain, Hungary, Switzerland, Australia, China, Italy, Austria and Slovenia. Both Aldi Nord and Aldi S√ºd also operate in the United States with 1,600 stores as of 2017.rliest roots of the company trace back to 1913, when the mother of¬†Karl¬†and¬†Theo Albrecht¬†opened a small store in a suburb of¬†Essen.Their father was employed as a miner and later as a baker's assistant. Karl Albrecht was born in 1920, Theo Albrecht in 1922. Theo Albrecht completed an apprenticeship in his mother's store, while Karl Albrecht worked in a¬†delicatessen.
Karl Albrecht took over a food shop formerly run by F. W. Judt who already advertised that they were the "cheapest food source". Karl Albrecht served in the¬†German Army¬†during¬†World War II. In 1946, the brothers took over their mother's business and soon opened another retail outlet nearby.[9]¬†By 1950, the Albrecht brothers owned 13 stores in the¬†Ruhr Valley.
The brothers' idea, which was new at the time, was to subtract the legal maximum rebate of 3% before sale. The market leaders at the time, which often were¬†co-operatives, required their customers to collect rebate stamps, and to send them at regular intervals to reclaim their money. The Albrecht brothers also rigorously removed merchandise that did not sell from their shelves, cutting costs by neither advertising nor selling fresh produce, and keeping the size of their retail outlets small.
When the brothers split the company in 1960 over a dispute whether they should sell cigarettes,[11]¬†they owned 300 shops with a cash flow of¬†DM90 million yearly. In 1962, they introduced the name¬†Aldi‚Äîshort for¬†Albrecht-Diskont. Aldi Nord and Aldi S√ºd have been financially and legally separate since 1966, although both divisions' names may appear as if they were a single enterprise with certain¬†store brands¬†or when negotiating with¬†contractor¬†companies.
The individual groups were originally owned and managed jointly by the brothers. Karl Albrecht, who died in 2014, retained ownership of Aldi S√ºd with a personal wealth of ‚Ç¨17.2 billion that made him the richest man in Germany. The co-owners of Aldi Nord,¬†Berthold¬†and¬†Theo Albrecht Jr.¬†came close behind at ‚Ç¨16 billion. Dieter Schwarz, owner of¬†Lidl¬†and¬†Kaufland¬†came in third, with a fortune of ‚Ç¨11.5 billion.
Aldi started to expand internationally in 1967, when Aldi S√ºd acquired the grocery chain Hofer in¬†Austria;¬†Aldi Nord opened its first stores abroad in the¬†Netherlands¬†in 1973,and other countries followed. In 1976, Aldi opened its first store in the United States in Iowa,

Now after having the male checkout search us everytime we there and claim to search others but clearly doesn't and still gets hostile when we comply and show him out bags and shopping bags and say nothing I think I will leave this here... Like seriously what is going on? I get retail staff put up with alot but if you don't like the pleasantries for the job. Get another job. Further more I wonder what you think of yourselves racially vilifying  people that clearly you don't like the look off because they look different or are against the grain in appearance this does not make people thieves. Is that the portrayal of the stores ethics?  Discrimination is really rife from what I see. I reckon the staff needs a refresher on how to treat people and management relook at the code of conduct in the way the customers are treated before you get yourself in trouble with the human rights Commission of Australia.

review_text:
The stock range here is not as big as some other Aldis.

The checkout queues are long but that's with most Aldis, not just this one. The service is as expected, very little to say otherwise.

Transport access is not too bad, buses stop on Ashley St. and South Rd. Car parking is quite plentiful, even at peak times.

Overall, it's good if you are in the local area. I wouldn't visit this one for a specific product though.

name: ALDI
review_text:
Best one for weekly grocery. I've noticed that the prices are at least 10% cheaper than other stores.

I would go on a weekday morning, to avoid crowds. Weekends are relatively crowded.

Ample parking available. However not undercover. Don't leave your kids in the car on sunny days.

Only downside is that the trolly decks in the car park are at the middle.
